.TH ASMREF "June 2026" "asmref" "Miscellaneous Information Manual"
.SH NAME
asmref \- Cheat sheet for Linux syscalls, architectures and assembly basics


.SH DESCRIPTION
This man page is a cheat sheet for assembly instructions, different CPU architectures, and Linux syscall numbers.

The goal is to provide a well-organized reference sheet with useful information for low-level programming and reverse engineering.

.SH CONTENT
The cheat sheet includes:
.IP \(bu 2
Syscall numbers
.IP \(bu 2
Different architectures
.IP \(bu 2
Basic assembly-related concepts

.SH SYSCALLS

.SH OVERVIEW
A syscall (system call) is a controlled interface that allows user space (ring 3) to request services from the kernel (ring 0).

For example, operations like reading files or writing output require a syscall. When a syscall is executed, the CPU switches from user mode to kernel mode to execute privileged operations.

